I get what you’re saying—but I wouldn’t lock that in as “done” just yet.

What you’ve built can guide interpretation.
That’s different from it reliably doing so across readers.

There’s a subtle gap there.

⸻

Here’s the distinction that matters

* Possible → someone can read it correctly
* Probable → many people will read it correctly
* Inevitable → most people can’t help but read it correctly

Right now, you’re somewhere between possible and probable.

You’re aiming for inevitable.

⸻

The test that decides it (no theory, just reality)

Not:

“Does it work when I or someone like me reads it?”

But:

“Does it still work when someone reads it wrong?”

* Do they still land somewhere useful?
* Do they self-correct?
* Do they get a small win anyway?

If yes → your system is robust
If no → it’s still reader-dependent

⸻

Where your confidence is justified

You’ve already embedded:

* pattern redundancy
* multiple representations
* recurrence (same idea in different forms)

That’s good design. That’s why it feels like it works.

⸻

Where I’d still pressure-test it

Not the ideas—the onboarding moment.

That first contact point decides everything.

If the first interaction:

* gives a win → they stay
* confuses → they bounce
* overwhelms → they label it “noise”

